#chapter(17, "An usual karaoke session")[
  And thus, Narumi Mona entered the karaoke booth.

  She never had the chance to do karaoke in middle school, since she did not
  get too close with anyone to be invited over. Another reason was that she knew
  nothing about pop songs, so she could not sing anything that any high schooler
  would know of.

  Don't get it wrong. She loved her fair share of idol music, but that could not
  be further than what young people actually listened to. And the limited amount
  of pop songs that she knew was through idol covers, to the point that she
  did not know who the original artist of these covers were,
  but only which idol actually covered the song. Despite the fact that the name
  of the original artist was right there in the title.

  Today, she was invited by her friend, Kazugai Uta, to go with her friend group
  for a group karaoke. Mikoto was not joining because of club activities, so Uta
  was the only person she knew there.

  When Uta invited her over, she thought to herself, _"I can't let this chance
  go to waste!"_, and now she was walking with the group.

  She clung to the sleeve of Uta, which kind of caught her friend off guard.

  Soon enough, Mona's group entered the karaoke booth. Since it was her first
  time there, Mona took glances around the place like a curious kid exploring
  her neighborhood. She had heard of going to karaoke shop many times before,
  both from her older friends and her idols, but now she could finally truly
  experience it first-hand.

  A boy from the group went to the stall to book a room for everyone,
  while everyone was doing small talk. Uta was happily chatting with her new
  friend, which Mona did not know the name of,
  while Mona had some questions thrown at her, but there was nothing
  much that could maintain a conversation on its own.

  _"Uta is so amazing, she could talk to everyone like it's nothing..."_

  Around her, there was a couple of smaller groups about to enter their
  respective booth. Another thing that caught her eyes was the juice dispenser,
  which Mona had seen before in fast food restaurants, but it seemed like this
  one was self-served. Next to it was a shelf containing all sorts of silly
  attachments, from animal ears to colored wigs.

  _"I like the cat ear thing, but everyone would probably think that it's too
  childish."_

  Other than the classic cat and dog ears, there were animal ears of different
  animals, too. There were quite a lot of horse ears, which seemed to originate
  from that gacha game about horse racing. Mona did not play that game, but some
  idols she knew voiced some characters there.

  Her focus switch back to the group. It seemed that the boy has finished
  booking and returned, so everyone started moving. The group, one by one,
  walked through the narrow stairway to the second floor, where all of the
  booths resided at.

  Mona was following right after Uta, hence being the last person in the line. After
  navigating through the second floor hall, the group finally arrived at the
  karaoke room, where they would spend the next three hours at. Everyone quickly
  got down to their respective seats, and of course, Mona took the seat right
  next to Uta, her guardian angel for today.

  Now that Mona had noticed it, there were quite a lot of boys in the group,
  which was a rare sight for her.
  To Mona, seeing girls was already a rare enough occasion, and
  since she usually had no business with the other gender, she was not used to
  hanging around boys at all. There were a couple of boys in the crowd
  surrounding her in the past few days, but honestly, the most she could
  remember was them asking for a signature from her sister and nothing more.

  Mona took a quick look around. The wall was full of soundproof foam, with the
  colorful lights from the ceiling that really lighten up the mood. Though the
  TV screen was quite smaller than the TV at home, it should be no problem
  reading the lyrics from it when one sings.

  Everyone settled down, but no one had the intention of choosing a song, let
  alone singing. Well, except a person, that was.

  "I guess I'm gonna sing first, then."

  Uta's voice disrupted the on-going whispers within the group. _"So cool, she's
  like a natural leader"_, Mona thought. Ever since when, she had taken the
  controller tablet and enqueue her song on the list.

  Since she was sitting right next to Uta,
  Mona took a quick look at the tablet out of curiosity. While waiting at the
  hall, she had decided on some songs
  to sing (mostly idol covers of pop song), but she wanted to see what her
  friend chose. As a reference.

  // we know what this is, right?
  "Hmm... _You, My Little Who Remains_ by Akatsuki, if I'm not reading that
  wrong... Haven't heard of this song before."

  Mona looked the song up on the Internet. _"Just 100,000 views? This song is
  really not too popular, isn't it?"_ She expected Uta to choose a song that was
  more mainstream, as it would fit her more, so she was kind of surprised by her
  friend's selection.

  She scrolled down the comment section of the song to see quite
  a lot of praises, surprisingly more than what a 100,000 views music video
  would regularly get.

  _"This does look similar to a hidden gem, if I'm not mistaken..."_

  Mona did see this kind of unusual engagement in her idols' videos, too. In the
  idol world, there were quite a lot of talented idols which unfortunately was
  not as mainstream as their counterparts, and only the most dedicated idol
  otaku would know about them. They were often considered "hidden gems" of
  idol culture, stars that only the most dedicated fans would know.

  So, by the looks of things, this might make sense, actually. A girl like Uta,
  with an enormous amount of knowledge about pop culture, would pick something
  like this as a way to prove herself.

  Then, the music started.

  // ABSOLUTE FUCKING ESCAPE
  "These moments of fleeting love... I can't get enough of it!"

  Uta's voice echoed throughout the room, much to the enjoyment of the whole
  group. For the entire time, Mona could not leave her eyes off of her friend,
  as if she was watching a real idol show. The lighting even made Uta shined
  brighter, which made Mona realized about the true purpose of such decorations.
  She did not even care about the
  animated music video on the TV screen either, which looked like a story of a
  salarywoman in an abusive workplace. Not sure how all of that related to the
  diabetically sweet tune of the song, though.

  The four minutes of the song went by in an instant. The music stopped, and
  what's left was only a brief moment of pure silence,
  before a round of grand applause for the seemingly perfect performance.
  It seemed that
  everyone else was flabbergasted by the sheer display of Uta's talents. Even
  Mona was loudly clapping her hand, too.

  "Amazing!" A girl yelled from the cheering crowd.

  "Hehe... It's nothing, really."

  Uta beamed back with a bright smile, which seemed to make the boys' heart
  skipped a beat.

  "Well, continuing Kazugai-san's otherworldly performance, I guess I'm gonna go
  next." The girl who Uta was talking to earlier stood up after finished picking
  her song on the controller
  tablet. She came to the mini-stage to receive the microphone from Uta's hand,
  before the music to the next song started.

  Once Uta got back to her seat, Mona could finally gather up the courage she
  needed to ask her friend for a favor.

  "Uhmm- Uta, can you help me a bit here?"

  "Sure, what's it?"

  "Since I only know idol songs, I'm not sure what to sing when my turn comes...
  You know any idol songs that would be popular with everyone? Like idol covers
  for example?"

  Mona did have a list of potential songs she could sing, but she was not really
  sure which among them would be a good pick. Seeing how perfect her friend was,
  she finally decided to ask for help from Uta instead.

  Uta pulled the tablet over for her timid friend. Most of the idol songs Mona
  knew was not even available, so she could not sing them even if she wanted to.
  Though, in the first place, she did not want to anyway, as that would
  instantly out her as a creepy idol nerd.

  "How about this? You think you can sing this?" Uta, having finally found a
  song suitable for her friend, pointed on the song title.

  "Hmm- maybe this could work... But is the original song really that popular?"

  "Yeah, the last time I've checked, it got about 300,000 million views, so...
  You wanted to sing this after Rika?"

  _"Oh, so this girl is Rika? Noted!"_

  "Uhm- I think I can." Mona replied.

  "Are you sure? Like do you need some time to compose yourself up first?" Uta
  tried to give her friend some preparation, "I know public gathering can be hard
  for you, so don't force yourself."

  Mona lightly nodded. "Well, if you say so..." Uta enqueued the song for her
  friend, before giving her a "Well, you got this!"

  The two finally switched their attention back to the mini karaoke stage. The
  song was just entering the third chorus, with an explosive and catchy tune.
  Even though the girl, apparently named Rika, did not have as great of a voice
  as Uta, she was still able to gather the attention of the crowd, and her voice
  was still burning with passion.

  Soonly enough, the song ended, and it's Mona's turn to sing.

  "Oh! It's Narumi-san's turn."

  "Sena-san has a really great voice, so I'm looking forward to this!"

  "Can you stop including Narumi Sena into this please, Narumi-san must be
  so--- tired of being her own sister's shadow..."

  It seemed that everyone in the group was able to get along with each other
  now, to the point that they could give each others some silly
  banters. Though, the sudden spike in conversation was making Mona quite
  nervous.

  "Come on, Mona! You got this!"

  Uta's cheering voice seemed to give Mona the final push she needed.

  Mona held the microphone close to her mouth, preparing for the coming first
  verse.

  Mona raised her voice to sing.
  Initially, her voice was somewhat low, even though it was already magnified by
  the microphone, but this situation gradually improved as Mona gained quite
  some confidence.

  The song finally ended, and Mona returned to her seat after a round of
  applause. It seemed like she was getting less praises than the first two,
  which made her feel a little bit down.

  "Good job, Mona!" Uta gave Mona her support, "That's pretty good for a first
  time!"

  Mona gave her friend a smile, before noticing a peticularity in her friend's
  encouragement.

  "Thanks... But how did you know it's my first time?" Mona replied, worrily
  asked if she slipped out something embarassing.

  "I mean, you do be staring at various things at the lobby."

  _"Aargh!"_ Mona screamed from the inside of her mind. She had let people see
  that she was an old-fashioned girl who never entered any karaoke booth. How
  will she ever recover from this...

  From the outside, on the other hand, she tried to brush things off with a
  faint smile.

  Even so, this karaoke session with Uta had truly made her appreciate her
  friend even more. Not only was she a natural leader, but she was also very
  thoughtful when it comes to her friends.

  Though Mona had said thanks to Uta a
  couple of times by now, there was still that urge in her to say those words
  again and again.

  Of course, her timidity would not let her do so so easily.
]
